cashire, England","Salmesbury, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"England","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 14 October 1194–Abt 1277":"circa 14 oktober 1194–circa 1277","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1193–1227":"1193–1227","1220–1256":"1220–1256","1160–1240":"1160–1240","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1216":"1216","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1277":"circa 1277","1256":"1256","14 October 1194":"14 oktober 1194","1277":"1277","January 1256":"januari 1256","about 1220":"circa 1220","about 14 October 1194":"circa 14 oktober 1194","Salmesbury Hall, Salmesbury, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Salmesbury, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"England","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 14 October 1194–Abt 1277":"about 14 October 1194–about 1277","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1193–1227":"1193–1227","1220–1256":"1220–1256","1160–1240":"1160–1240","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1216":"1216","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1277":"about 1277","1256":"1256","14 October 1194":"14 October 1194","1277":"1277","January 1256":"January 1256","about 1220":"about 1220","about 14 October 1194":"about 14 October 1194","Salmesbury Hall, Salmesbury, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Salmesbury, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"England","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"FitzWalter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , ‘son of  <i>Walter</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzwater","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Fitzwalter</b>, a patronymic from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , meaning ‘son of <i>Walter</i>’.","History: This is the name of a family of Norman origin, descended from Godfrey, Count of Brionne (died <i>c.</i> 1010). Godfrey's grandson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":64,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret FitzWalter was born about 14 October 1194, in Preston, Lancashire, England as the daughter of Walter FitzOsbert. She married Roger de Samlesbury in 1216, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1277, in Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 84."},"et":{"about 14 October 1194–Abt 1277":"umbes 14. oktoober 1194–umbes 1277","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1193–1227":"1193–1227","1220–1256":"1220–1256","1160–1240":"1160–1240","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1216":"1216","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1277":"umbes 1277","1256":"1256","14 October 1194":"14. oktoober 1194","1277":"1277","January 1256":"jaanuar 1256","about 1220"